The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, July 28, 2004 				 Hughes net jumps 63%
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, July 27: Hughes Software Systems (HSS) registered a 63 per cent jump in net profit at Rs 24.7 crore representing a strong growth over the corresponding quarter last year. 																								The company recorded a 42 per cent growth in sales at Rs 108.3 crore during the quarter ended June 30, 2004. Total income during the quarter stood at Rs 111.5 crore.																								The companys earning per share of Rs 7.28 per cent represents a 61 per cent growth over the corresponding quarter last year. HSS added 18 new customers during the period.																								HSS, along with its subsidiary, had a net profit of Rs 24.6 crore on a sales turnover of Rs 109.4 crore. Total income stood at Rs 112.6 crore and the basic earnings per share was Rs 7.24.																								During the second quarter of financial year 2004-05, sales are expected to grow by 5-6 per cent on a quarter-on-quarter basis, while the profit after tax margin is expected to be about 21-22 per cent.																								HSS chairman Ash Bhardwaj said, By partnering with HSS, Flextronics is the first enterprise management service provider to offer embedded and application software development for telecom infrastructure products and customers. Flextronics can now provide complete outsourcing solutions to telecom OEMs.																								Arun Kumar, president and managing director of HSS, said, HSS has had a great beginning to fiscal 2005. Our results reflect our stated commitment to predictability and consistency. Since the time we identified financial consistency as a key objective, we have had eight straight quarters of steady predictability and growth.																								NIIT net jumps 12 fold																								NIIT Ltd and its subsidiaries registered a 12-fold jump in net profit at Rs 7.5 crore in the first quarter ended June 30.																								The company reported an operating profit of Rs 12.9 crore leading to an operating profit margin of 13 per cent, which is an improvement of 126 basis points.																								The net profit, after accounting for profit share of associates, stood at Rs 10.9 crore reflecting an earning per share of Rs 5.60. Global system-wide revenues grew by 10 per cent at Rs 152 crore.																								Consolidated net revenue of NIIT and its subsidiaries also grew by 10 per cent at Rs 96.8 crore year-on-year basis.																								NIITs overseas operations had good business with a 53 per cent jump at Rs 81.2 crore. The remaining 47 per cent was generated from its learning business in India. Individual learning segment in India contributed Rs 39.6 crore, while the India Institutional business contributed Rs 31.2 crore during the quarter.																								Rajendra S. Pawar, chairman of NIIT, said, The 12-fold growth in net profit reflects increased productivity and the increasing confidence of customers in NIIT. 
